children.name: arubaWiredMgmdRmonTrapMIB
children.description: This MIB module describes objects to configure RMON traps.

children.name: arubaWiredMgmdRmonTrapEvent
children.description: The event ID for which the trap is set has occured.

children.name: arubaWiredPoeMIB
children.description: This MIB module describes management objects that manage Power Source Equipment (PSE). This is the MIB module related to HPE Aruba PoE

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortTable
children.description: A table of objects that display and control the power characteristics of power Ethernet ports on a Power Source Entity (PSE) device. This group will be implemented in managed power Ethernet switches and mid-span devices. Values of all read-write objects in this table are persistent at restart/reboot.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortEntry
children.description: The fields in these entries will be used to supplement fields in 'pethPsePortEntry in ieee802af.mib.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPowerAllocateBy
children.description: Allows control over the power allocation strategy used for this port. Two power allocation strategies are class(2) and usage(1). When allocating by usage(1) power is delivered as requested by a PD. When allocating by class(2) the PSE uses the power ramp-up signature of the PD to identify the PD's power class and use the power level for the specified class. Enumeration: 'usage': 1, 'class': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPreStdDetect
children.description: This field specifies the pre standard detect configuration for this port. A value of on - indicates that pre-802.3af-standard devices to power on. A value of off - indicates that only pre-802.3at/bt compliant devices are allowed. The default value is off. Enumeration: 'on': 2, 'off': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortRpd
children.description: Rapid Power Down is executed by the hardware in the event of a power-supply failure. It quickly cuts power to a PD to prevent an over-current scenario in the PSE. This field indicates whether the interface will go down in the event of any PSU failure or not. A value of on(2) indicates that a power supply failure will cause the power delivery to be cut on supply failure. A value of off(1) indicates that the port is unaffected by the failure of any single PSU.The default value is off(1). Enumeration: 'on': 2, 'off': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortCurrent
children.description: This field specifies the current supplied at this port. This value is specified in milliamperes(mA).

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortVoltage
children.description: This field specifies the Voltage supplied at this port. This value is specified in 10's of Volts (dV).

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortReservedPower
children.description: This field specifies quantum of power which has been reserved for the PD at this port. This value is specified in milliwatts (mW).

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPowerDrawn
children.description: This field specifies quantum of power which has indicating the actual power drawn by powered device(PD). This value is specified in milliwatts (mW).

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortAveragePower
children.description: This field specifies the average power in milliwatts drawn by the powered device (PD) on this port.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPeakPower
children.description: This field specifies the peak power supplied in milliwatts to the powered device (PD) connected to this port.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortOperStatus
children.description: This field specifies the operational status of the port. Enumeration: 'on': 3, 'deny': 1, 'off': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPdSignature
children.description: This Signature value represents the PD signature. This variable is valid only while a PD is detected. In 802.3af and 802.3at standards the power controller on the PSE uses two of the four pairs of wires in the RJ45 connector to supply power to a power controller on the PD. With 802.3bt standard the controller on the PSE uses all four pairs. On the PD side there can either be single power controller, or two distinct power controllers connected to each of the two pairs and each of the two controllers would negotiate and draw power independently from the PSE. The Controller on the PSE is capable of detecting the PD signature, which will indicate whether the PD comprises a single controller or two independent controllers. Possible values: unknownSignature : 2-pair mode, singleSignature : 4-pair mode and one controller on the PD side, dualSignature : 4-pair mode and two controllers on the PD side. Enumeration: 'unknownSignature': 0, 'dualSignature': 2, 'singleSignature': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPowerClassification
children.description: A read-only value that indicates the PD Class of a detected PD. Classification is a way to tag different terminals on the Power over LAN network according to their power consumption. Devices such as IP telephones, WLAN access points and others, will be classified according to their power requirements. The meaning of the classification labels is defined in the IEEE specification. This variable is valid only while a PD is being powered, that is, while the attribute pethPsePortDetectionStatus is reporting the enumeration deliveringPower. Enumeration: 'class8': 9, 'class6': 7, 'class7': 8, 'class4': 5, 'class5': 6, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class0': 1, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPseAssignedClass
children.description: This field indicates the actual class assigned by PSE to the PD. Class demotion allows the PSE to allocate less than the PD requested power based on the PD requested power and PSE available power. This information is published to the PD via the LLDP protocol. This read-only value indicates the PSE assigned class on this port. This variable is valid only while a PD is being powered, that is, while the attribute pethPsePortDetectionStatus is reporting the enumeration deliveringPower. Enumeration: 'class6': 7, 'class4': 5, 'class5': 6, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class0': 1, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseFourPairPortTable
children.description: A table of objects that display and control the power characteristics of power Ethernet ports on a Power Source Entity (PSE) device. This group will be implemented in managed power Ethernet switches and mid-span devices. Values of all read-write objects in this table are persistent at restart/reboot.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseFourPairPortEntry
children.description: The fields in these entries will be used to supplement fields in 'pethPsePortEntry in ieee802af.mib.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortDetectionStatusPairA
children.description: Describes the operational status of the port PD detection. A value of deliveringPowerAltA - indicates that the PSE State diagram is in the state POWER_ON_PRI if alt_pri='a', or the state POWER_ON_SEC if alt_pri='b'. A value of faultAltA - indicates that the PSE State diagram is in the state IDLE_PRI if alt_pri='a', or the state IDLE_SEC if alt_pri='b' due to the variable error_condition_pri = TRUE (if alt_pri='a') or error_condition_sec = TRUE (if alt_pri='b'). A value of searchingAltA - indicates the PSE State diagram is in a state other than those listed above. Enumeration: 'deliveringPowerAltA': 2, 'searchingAltA': 1, 'faultAltA': 3.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortDetectionStatusPairB
children.description: Describes the operational status of the port PD detection. A value of deliveringPowerAltB - indicates that the PSE State diagram is in the state POWER_ON_SEC if alt_pri='a', or the state POWER_ON_PRI if alt_pri='b'. A value of faultAltB - indicates that the PSE State diagram is in the state IDLE_SEC if alt_pri='a', or the state IDLE_PRI if alt_pri='b' due to the variable error_condition_sec = TRUE (if alt_pri='a') or error_condition_pri = TRUE (if alt_pri='b'). A value of searchingAltB - indicates the PSE State diagram is in a state other than those listed above. Enumeration: 'searchingAltB': 1, 'deliveringPowerAltB': 2, 'faultAltB': 3.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPowerClassificationPairA
children.description: A read-only value that indicates the PD Class of a detected dual-signature PD on paira. Classification is a way to tag different terminals on the Power over LAN network according to their power consumption. Devices such as IP telephones, WLAN access points and others, will be classified according to their power requirements. The meaning of the classification labels is defined in the IEEE specification. This variable is valid only while a PD is being powered that is, while the attribute arubaWiredPoePethPsePortDetectionStatusPairA is reporting the enumeration deliveringPowerAltA. Enumeration: 'class4': 4, 'class5': 5, 'class2': 2, 'class3': 3, 'class1': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPowerClassificationPairB
children.description: A read-only value that indicates the PD Class of a detected dual-signature PD on paira. Classification is a way to tag different terminals on the Power over LAN network according to their power consumption. Devices such as IP telephones, WLAN access points and others, will be classified according to their power requirements. The meaning of the classification labels is defined in the IEEE specification. This variable is valid only while a PD is being powered, that is, while the attribute arubaWiredPoePethPsePortDetectionStatusPairB is reporting the enumeration deliveringPowerAltB. Enumeration: 'class4': 4, 'class5': 5, 'class2': 2, 'class3': 3, 'class1': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPseAssignedClassA
children.description: This field indicates the actual class assigned by PSE to the PD. Class demotion allows the PSE to allocate less than the PD requested power based on the PD requested power and PSE available power. This information is published to the PD via the LLDP protocol. This read-only value indicates the PSE assigned class to PairA of this port. Enumeration: 'class4': 4, 'class2': 2, 'class3': 3, 'class1': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPseAssignedClassB
children.description: This field indicates the actual class assigned by PSE to the PD. Class demotion allows the PSE to allocate less than the PD requested power based on the PD requested power and PSE available power. This information is published to the PD via the LLDP protocol. This read-only value indicates the PSE assigned class to PairA of this port. Enumeration: 'class4': 4, 'class2': 2, 'class3': 3, 'class1': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortInvalidSignatureCounterPairA
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram enters the state SIGNATURE_INVALID, if alt_pri='a'.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortInvalidSignatureCounterPairB
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram enters the state SIGNATURE_INVALID, if alt_pri='b'

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPowerDeniedCounterPairA
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram enters the state POWER_DENIED, if alt_pri='a'.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortPowerDeniedCounterPairB
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram enters the state POWER_DENIED, if alt_pri='b'.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortOverLoadCounterPairA
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram enters the state ERROR_DELAY_OVER, if alt_pri='a'.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortOverLoadCounterPairB
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram enters the state ERROR_DELAY_OVER, if alt_pri='b'.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortMPSAbsentCounterPairA
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram transitions directly from the state POWER_ON to the state IDLE due to tmpdo_timer_done being asserted, if alt_pri='a'.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortMPSAbsentCounterPairB
children.description: This counter is incremented when the PSE state diagram transitions directly from the state POWER_ON to the state IDLE due to tmpdo_timer_done being asserted, if alt_pri='b'.

children.name: arubaWiredPoeCompliance
children.description: A compliance statement for HP Routing switches with PoE capability.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPsePortTableGroup
children.description: A collection of objects display configuration, status, PD information and mesurements of PoE PSE Port table.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseFourPairPortTableGroup
children.description: A collection of objects display four pair paramentets of each pair PD information, status, and counters of PoE PSE Port table.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethMainPseTableGroup
children.description: A Collection of Object(s) that provide information about each power source equipment instance.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseModuleTableGroup
children.description: A Collection of Object(s) that provide AlwaysOnPoe information about each module on switch.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethMainPseTable
children.description: A table of objects that display and control attributes of the main power source in a PSE device. Ethernet switches are one example of boxes that would support these objects. Values of all read-write objects in this table are persistent at restart/reboot.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethMainPseEntry
children.description: The fields in these entries will be used to supplement fields in 'pethMainPseEntry in ieee802af.mib.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethMainPseReservedPower
children.description: This field specifies the power in Watts, in the switch available for PoE power delivery. This power is available only for subsystems of type chassis, as power supplies are associated with chassis subsystem.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethMainPseFailoverPower
children.description: This field specifies the power in Watts, in the switch available for PoE power delivery when a single power supply failure happens. This power is available only for subsystems of type chassis, as power supplies are associated with chassis subsystem.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethMainPseRedundantPower
children.description: This field specifies power in Watts reserved by power supply based on power redundancy configurations. This power is available only for subsystems of type chassis, as power supplies are associated with chassis subsystem.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseModuleTable
children.description: A table of objects contains the AlwaysOnPoe status information on module.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseModuleEntry
children.description: The fields in these entries will be used to display alwaysonpoe status information on specific module.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseModuleGroupIndex
children.description: This variable uniquely identifies the group containing the module to which a power Ethernet PSE is connected. Group means box in the stack and the value 1 MUST be used for non-modular devices.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseModuleSlotIndex
children.description: This variable uniquely identifies the module in a switch and value 1 must be used for non-modular devices.

children.name: arubaWiredPoePethPseModuleAlwaysOnPoe
children.description: Alwayson PoE is a feature that provides the ability for a switch to continue to provide power across a soft reboot. Value on(2) indicates Always-on PoE feature is enabled on the subsystem. Value off(1) indicates Alwayson PoE feature is disabled on the subsystem. This feature is applicable to subsystems of type chassis in non-modular switches, and to subsystems of type line-card in modular switches. This configuration is ignored on a non-PoE capable subsystems. Enumeration: 'on': 2, 'off': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpMIB
children.description: This MIB module describes management objects that manage LLDP information related to Power Source Equipment (PSE). This is the MIB module related to HPE Aruba LLDP

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerTable
children.description: This table contains one row per port of power ethernet information (as a part of the LLDP 802.3bt organizational extension) on the local system known to this agent.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerEntry
children.description: Information about a particular port component.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerPortClass
children.description: The value that identifies the port Class of the given port associated with the local system. Enumeration: 'pClassPD': 2, 'pClassPSE': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerMDISupported
children.description: The truth value used to indicate whether the MDI power is supported on the given port associated with the local system.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerMDIEnabled
children.description: The truth value used to indicate whether the MDI power is enabled on given port associated with the local system.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerPairControlable
children.description: The truth value used to indicate the ability to control which PSE Pinout Alternative is used for PD detection and power.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerPairs
children.description: The truth value that identifies the PSE Pinout Alternative in use for detecting and supplying power to the PD. Enumeration: 'pairSignal': 1, 'pairSpare': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerClass
children.description: The truth value that indicates the requested Class of the PD. Enumeration: 'class4': 5, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class0': 1, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerType
children.description: This field reflects the actual local power type. Enumeration: 'type2PD': 2, 'type1PD': 4, 'type1PSE': 3, 'type2PSE': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerSource
children.description: This field reflects the requested local device power source. When the power type is PSE, this field shall be set to primary(2) when the PSE is sourcing its power through the PI from its primary supply; to backup(3) when the PSE is sourcing its power through the PI from a backup source; and to unknown(1) when this information is not available. Enumeration: 'unknown': 1, 'reserved': 4, 'backup': 3, 'primary': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerPriority
children.description: This field reflects the requested local device power priority. When the power type is PD, this field shall be set to the power priority configured for the device. If a PD is unable to determine its power priority or it has not been configured, then this field shall be set to unknown(1). When the power type is PSE, this field shall be set to unknown(1). Enumeration: 'high': 3, 'unknown': 1, 'critical': 2, 'low': 4.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPDRequestedPowerValue
children.description: It indicates the maximum input average power the PD is requesting in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPDRequestedPowerValueA
children.description: It indicates the PD requested power value for the Mode A pairset in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPDRequestedPowerValueB
children.description: It indicates the PD requested power value for the Mode B pairset in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPSEAllocatedPowerValue
children.description: It indicates the maximum input average power the PSE expects the PD to draw in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPSEAllocatedPowerValueA
children.description: It indicates the maximum input average power levels the PSE expects the dual-signature PD to draw, in units of 0.1 W, on Alternative A, when the PSE provides power over 4-pair.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPSEAllocatedPowerValueB
children.description: It indicates the maximum input average power levels the PSE expects the dual-signature PD to draw, in units of 0.1 W, on Alternative B, when the PSE provides power over 4-pair.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPSEPoweringStatus
children.description: This field reflects the existing powering configuration of the PSE and thus indicates that the PSE is using the 'PSE allocated power value' field or is using the 'PSE allocated power value Alternative A' field and 'PSE allocated power value Alternative B' field. For a PD the contents of this attribute are undefined. Enumeration: 'fourPdualsigPD': 3, 'twoPair': 1, 'fourPsinglesigPD': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerPairsExt
children.description: This field indicates the supported PSE Pinout Alternative. For a PD the contents of this attribute are undefined Enumeration: 'both': 3, 'altB': 2, 'altA': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerClassExtA
children.description: For a dual-signature PD, it indicates the requested Class for Mode A during Physical Layer Classification. For a single-signature PD, a read-only value set to 'singlesig'. For a PSE connected to a dual-signature PD, a read-only value that indicates the currently assigned Class for Mode A. For a PSE connected to a single-signature PD, or a PSE that operates only in 2-pair mode, the value is set to 'singlesig' Enumeration: 'singlesig': 1, 'class4': 5, 'class5': 6, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerClassExtB
children.description: For a dual-signature PD, it indicates the requested Class for Mode B during Physical Layer Classification. For a single-signature PD, a read-only value set to 'singlesig'. For a PSE connected to a dual-signature PD, a read-only value that indicates the currently assigned Class for Mode B. For a PSE connected to a single-signature PD, or a PSE that operates only in 2-pair mode, the value is set to 'singlesig' Enumeration: 'singlesig': 1, 'class4': 5, 'class5': 6, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerClassExt
children.description: For a single-signature PD, it indicates the requested Class during Physical Layer Classification. For a dual-signature PD, the value is set to 'dualsig'. For a PSE connected to a single-signature PD or a PSE that operates only in 2-pair mode, a readonly value that indicates the currently assigned Class. For a PSE connected to a dualsignature PD, a read-only value set to 'dualsig'. Enumeration: 'dualsig': 1, 'class8': 9, 'class6': 7, 'class7': 8, 'class4': 5, 'class5': 6, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPowerTypeExt
children.description: This field indicates if the local system is a Type 3 or Type 4 PSE or PD, and in the case of a Type 3 or Type 4 PD, if it is a single-signature PD or a dual-signature PD Enumeration: 'type3dualsigPD': 4, 'type4singlesigPD': 5, 'type4PSE': 2, 'type3singlesigPD': 3, 'type4dualsigPD': 6, 'type3PSE': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPDLoad
children.description: The truth value used to indicate whether the load of a dual- signature PD is electrically isolated. For a single-signature PD, or a PSE, the value of this attribute is FALSE.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPSEMaxAvailPower
children.description: It indicates the local PSE maximum available power value in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocPSEAutoclassSupport
children.description: It indicates whether the local PSE system supports Autoclass

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3LocAutoclassCompleted
children.description: It indicates whether the local PSE system has completed the Autoclass measurement

children.name: arubaWiredLldpLocPseTlvSentType
children.description: This field specifies the set of TLVs that are actually sent by the PSE Enumeration: 'dot3': 2, 'med': 1, 'dot3-ext': 3.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpLocPdTlvSentType
children.description: This field specifies the set of TLVs that are actually sent by the PD Enumeration: 'dot3': 2, 'med': 1, 'dot3-ext': 3, 'medanddot3': 4, 'medanddot3-ext': 5.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerTable
children.description: This table contains one row per port of power ethernet information (as a part of the LLDP 802.3bt organizational extension) on the remote system known to this agent.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerEntry
children.description: Information about a particular port component.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerPortClass
children.description: The value that identifies the port Class of the given port associated with the remote system. Enumeration: 'pClassPD': 2, 'pClassPSE': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerMDISupported
children.description: The truth value used to indicate whether the MDI power is supported on the given port associated with the remote system.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerMDIEnabled
children.description: The truth value used to indicate whether the MDI power is enabled on given port associated with the remote system.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerPairControlable
children.description: The truth value used to indicate the ability to control which PSE Pinout Alternative is used for PD detection and power.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerPairs
children.description: The truth value that identifies the PSE Pinout Alternative in use for detecting and supplying power to the PD. Enumeration: 'pairSignal': 1, 'pairSpare': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerClass
children.description: The truth value that indicates the requested Class of the PD. Enumeration: 'class4': 5, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class0': 1, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerType
children.description: This field reflects the actual remote power type. Enumeration: 'type2PD': 2, 'type1PD': 4, 'type1PSE': 3, 'type2PSE': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerSource
children.description: This field reflects the remote device (PD) requested power source. This field is encoded as pseAndLocal(4) when a PD being powered both locally and by a PSE, to local(3) when the PD being powered locally only, and to pse(2) when the PD is being powered by a PSE Enumeration: 'unknown': 1, 'pseAndLocal': 4, 'local': 3, 'pse': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerPriority
children.description: This field reflects the requested remote device power priority. When the power type is PD, this field shall be set to the power priority configured for the device. If a PD is unable to determine its power priority or it has not been configured, then this field shall be set to unknown(1). When the power type is PSE, this field shall be set to unknown(1). Enumeration: 'high': 3, 'unknown': 1, 'critical': 2, 'low': 4.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPDRequestedPowerValue
children.description: It indicates the maximum input average power the PD is requesting in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPDRequestedPowerValueA
children.description: It indicates the PD requested power value for the Mode A pairset in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPDRequestedPowerValueB
children.description: It indicates the PD requested power value for the Mode B pairset in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPSEAllocatedPowerValue
children.description: It indicates the PSE allocated power value received from the remote system. For a PSE, it is the PSE allocated power value that was echoed back by the remote PD, in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPSEAllocatedPowerValueA
children.description: It indicates the PSE allocated power value for the Alternative A pairset received from the remote system. For a PSE, it is the PSE allocated power value for the Alternative A pairset that was echoed back by the remote PD, in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPSEAllocatedPowerValueB
children.description: It indicates the PSE allocated power value for the Alternative B pairset received from the remote system. For a PSE, it is the PSE allocated power value for the Alternative A pairset that was echoed back by the remote PD, in units of 0.1 W.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPDPoweredStatus
children.description: This field indicates the existing powered configuration of the PD and thus indicate that the PD is using the 'PD requested power value' field or is using the 'PD requested power value Mode A' field and the 'PD requested power value Mode B' field. For a PSE the contents of this attribute are undefined. Enumeration: 'twoPdualsigPD': 2, 'fourPdualsigPD': 3, 'singlesigPD': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerClassExtA
children.description: For a dual-signature PD, a read-only value that indicates the currently assigned Class for Mode A by the remote 4-pair PSE. For a single-signature PD, or a dual-signature PD connected to a 2-pair only PSE, a read-only value set to 'singlesig' by the remote PSE. For a PSE connected to a dualsignature PD, a read-only value that indicates the requested Class for Mode A during Physical Layer classification by the remote PD. For a PSE connected to a single-signature PD, a read-only value set to 'singlesig' by the remote PD Enumeration: 'singlesig': 1, 'class4': 5, 'class5': 6, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class1': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredLldpXdot3RemPowerClassExtB
children.description: For a dual-signature PD, a read-only value that indicates the currently assigned Class for Mode A by the remote 4-pair PSE. For a single-signature PD, or a dual-signature PD connected to a 2-pair only PSE, a read-only value set to 'singlesig' by the remote PSE. For a PSE connected to a dualsignature PD, a read-only value that indicates the requested Class for Mode B during Physical Layer classification by the remote PD. For a PSE connected to a single-signature PD, a read-only value set to 'singlesig' by the remote PD. Enumeration: 'singlesig': 1, 'class4': 5, 'class5': 6, 'class2': 3, 'class3': 4, 'class1': 2.

For a dual- signature PD connected to a 4-pair capable PSE, a read-only value set to 'dualsig' by the remote PSE. For a PSE connected to a single-signature PD, a read-only value that indicates the requested Class during Physical Layer classification by the remote PD. For a PSE connected to a dual-signature PD, a readonly value set to 'dualsig' by the remote PD. children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyTable
children.description: Contains copy configuration requests.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyEntry
children.description: A configuration copy request. A management station wishing to create an entry should first generate a random serial number to be used as the index to this sparse table. The station should then create the associated instance of the row status and row index objects. It must also, either in the same or in successive PDUs, create an instance of arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType and arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType. Only one of the source or destination file types can be 'externalFile'. If one of the file types is a 'externalFile', the following values are expected as well: - arubaWiredConfigurationCopyProtocol - arubaWiredConfigurationCopyFileName - arubaWiredConfigurationCopyServerAddressType - arubaWiredConfigurationCopyServerAddress If the 'externalFile' is the destination, then a valid arubaWiredConfigurationCopyFileFormat is required as well. If authentication is required, then both arubaWiredConfigurationCopyUserName and arubaWiredConfigurationCopyUserPassword are necessary. Once the appropriate instance of all the configuration objects have been created, either by an explicit SNMP set request or by default, the row status should be set to active to initiate the request. Note that this entire procedure may be initiated via a single set request which specifies a row status of createAndGo as well as specifies valid values for the non-defaulted configuration objects. Once the configuration copy request has been created (i.e. the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyEntryRowStatus has been made active), the entry cannot be modified - the only operation possible after this is to delete the row. Once the request completes, the management station should retrieve the values of the status objects of interest, and should then delete the entry. In order to prevent old entries from clogging the table, entries will be aged out, but an entry will never be deleted within 5 minutes of completing.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyIndex
children.description: Object which specifies a unique entry in the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyTable. A management station wishing to initiate a configuration copy operation should use a random value for this object when creating or modifying an instance of a ArubaWiredConfigurationCopyEntry. The RowStatus semantics of the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyEntryRowStatus object will prevent access conflicts.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType
children.description: Specifies the type of file to copy from. Either the arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType or the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType (or both) must be of type: - 'checkpoint' - 'runningConfiguration' - 'startupConfiguration' The arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType must be different from the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType
children.description: Specifies the type of file to copy to. Either the arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType or the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType (or both) must be of type: - 'checkpoint' - 'runningConfiguration' - 'startupConfiguration' The arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType must be different from the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyProtocol
children.description: The protocol file transfer protocol that should be used to copy the configuration file over the network. If the config file transfer is to occur locally on the SNMP agent, the method of transfer is left up to the implementation.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCheckpointName
children.description: Specifies the name of the checkpoint to copy. This object must be created when either the arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType or arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType has the value 'checkpoint'.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyFileFormat
children.description: File format to be used when exporting the configuration to a remote device. This value is ignored unless arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType is 'externalFile'.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyFileName
children.description: The name (including the path, if applicable) of the file. This object must be created when either the arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType or arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType has the value 'externalFile'.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyServerAddressType
children.description: This object indicates the transport type of the address contained in arubaWiredConfigurationCopyServerAddress object. This must be created when either the arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType or arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType has the value 'externalFile'.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyServerAddress
children.description: The network address of the remote server from (or to) which to copy the configuration. This object must be created when either the arubaWiredConfigurationCopySourceFileType or arubaWiredConfigurationCopyDestFileType has the value 'externalFile'. All bits as 0s or 1s for arubaWiredConfigurationCopyServerAddress are not allowed. The format of this address depends on the value of the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyServerAddressType object.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyUserName
children.description: Remote username for copy via the protocol stated in arubaWiredConfigurationCopyProtocol.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyUserPassword
children.description: Remote password for copy via the protocol stated in arubaWiredConfigurationCopyProtocol. This object must be created when the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyProtocol is: - scp - sftp Reading it returns a zero-length string for security reasons.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyVRFName
children.description: Remote vrf name for copy via the protocol stated in arubaWiredConfigurationCopyProtocol.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyNotificationOnCompletion
children.description: Specifies whether or not a arubaWiredConfigurationCopyCompletion notification should be issued on completion of the configuration transfer. If such a notification is desired, it is the responsibility of the management entity to ensure that the SNMP administrative model is configured in such a way as to allow the notification to be delivered.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyState
children.description: Specifies the state of this configuration copy request. This value of this object is instantiated only after the row has been instantiated, i.e. after the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyEntryRowStatus has been made active.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyTimeStarted
children.description: Specifies the time the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyState last transitioned to 'running', or 0 if the state has never transitioned to 'running' (e.g., stuck in 'waiting' state). This object is instantiated only after the row has been instantiated.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyTimeCompleted
children.description: Specifies the time the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyState last transitioned from 'running' to 'successful' or 'failed' states. This object is instantiated only after the row has been instantiated. Its value will remain 0 until the request has completed.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyFailureCause
children.description: The reason why the configuration copy operation failed. This object is instantiated only when the arubaWiredConfigurationCopyState for this entry is in the 'failed' state.

children.name: arubaWiredConfigurationCopyEntryRowStatus
children.description: The status of this table entry. Once the entry status is set to active, the associated entry cannot be modified until the request completes (arubaWiredConfigurationCopyState transitions to 'successful' or 'failed' state).

children.description: The configuration copy configuration.

children.description: A collection of configuration copy notifications objects.

children.name: arubaWiredPortSecurityPortTable
children.description: A list of port security configuration and status entries. The number of entries is determined by the number of ports in the system that can support the port security feature. Ports that are not port security capable will not be displayed in this table. This table includes ports on which port security parameters can be set even if port security feature itself cannot be enabled due to conflict with other features.

children.name: arubaWiredPortSecurityPortEntry
children.description: Port Security configuration information for a single port.

children.name: arubaWiredifIndex
children.description: Indicates the unique port index.

children.name: arubaWiredPortSecurityEnable
children.description: This object indicates whether port security feature is enabled on a port. The default value is false.

children.name: arubaWiredClientLimit
children.description: The maximum number (N) of MAC addresss to be secured on the interface. The first N MAC addresss learned or configured are made secured.

children.name: arubaWiredCurrentSecureMacAddrCount
children.description: The current number of MAC addresss secured on this interface.

children.name: arubaWiredViolationAction
children.description: Determines the action that the device will take if the traffic matches the port security violation. notify(1) - Send an SNMP trap and log an event when a violation occurs. shutdown(2) - Send an SNMP trap, log an event and shutdown the port when a violation occurs. Enumeration: 'notify': 1, 'shutdown': 2.

children.name: arubaWiredClientViolationStatus
children.description: Indicates whether this port is currently in violation state or not.

children.name: arubaWiredClientViolationReason
children.description: This object represents the reason for violation. none(0) - None of the violation is triggered. clientLimitExceeded(1) - Indicates whether the port is in a state where its client limit has been violated. This will be reset when the client limit reduces to below the threshold or the link goes down. stickyClientMove(2) - Indicates whether the port is in a state where sticky mac client move has been violated. This will be reset when the link goes down. Enumeration: 'none': 0, 'stickyClientMove': 2, 'clientLimitExceeded': 1.

children.name: arubaWiredClientLimitViolationCount
children.description: Number of client limit violations that have occurred on this port since system boot.

children.name: arubaWiredStickyClientMoveViolationCount
children.description: Number of sticky mac client move violations that have occurred on this port since system boot.

children.name: arubaWiredRecoveryTimer
children.description: Time in seconds after which the port will be re-enabled if it was shutdown in response to a violation event. This is only applicable if shutdown recovery is enabled.

children.name: arubaWiredShutdownRecovery
children.description: Enable auto-recovery for the port. This is only relevant when the violation action is set to shutdown. The port is re-enabled after the recovery timer has expired.

children.name: arubaWiredStickyEnable
children.description: Indicates whether port security sticky MAC learning is enabled on this port. This is only supported on physical ports.
